1 (IV) Comforting a person experiencing a mental health
2 or substance use crisis;
3 (V) Helping a person with a mental illness or substance
4 use disorder avoid a mental health or substance use crisis; and
5 (VI) Promoting healing, recovery and good mental
6 health.
7 3. The Department shall apply to the Secretary of Health and
8 Human Services for any waiver of federal law or apply for any
9 amendment of the State Plan for Medicaid that is necessary for
10 the Department to receive federal funding to provide the coverage
11 required by this section. The Department shall fully cooperate in
12 good faith with the Federal Government during the application
13 process to satisfy the requirements of the Federal Government for
14 obtaining a waiver or amendment pursuant to this section.
15 4. The Division shall coordinate with the Division of Public
16 and Behavioral Health of the Department to develop a model for
17 providing medical respite care to persons experiencing
18 homelessness. The model must accord with the standards
19 prescribed by the National Institute for Medical Respite Care, or
20 its successor organization, for programs providing medical respite
21 care, to the extent that those standards do not conflict with federal
22 or state law.
23 5. As used in this section:
24 (a) “Medical respite care” means acute and post-acute medical
25 care and other support services to persons who are experiencing
26 homelessness who:
27 (1) Are unable to completely recover from an illness, injury
28 or disease; and
29 (2) Do not require care from a hospital or other inpatient
30 medical facility.
31 (b) “Person experiencing homelessness” means a person who
32 is transient, at imminent risk of homelessness or homeless.
